Launch and Connect to an Amazon EC2 Instance
➤ Step 1: Open the AWS EC2 Service

• Log in to the AWS Management Console.
• Search for EC2 and open the EC2 Dashboard.

➤ Step 2: Launch a New Instance

• Click Launch Instance.
• Enter an instance name (example: Linux-Server).
• Under Amazon Machine Image (AMI), select a Linux OS such as:
– Ubuntu Server 22.04 LTS
– Amazon Linux 2 (Free Tier)

➤ Step 3: Choose an Instance Type

• Select t2.micro (Free Tier eligible).

➤ Step 4: Generate a Key Pair

• Click Create a new key pair.
• Choose RSA type and download the .pem file.
• This key will be used for SSH connection.

➤ Step 5: Configure Security Group

• Allow SSH (port 22) from your IP address.
• Leave other settings default.

➤ Step 6: Launch the Instance

• Click Launch Instance and wait until the status becomes Running.
• Copy the Public IP address from the instance details.

➤ Step 7: Connect to the EC2 Instance Using SSH

• Open a terminal on your system.
• Change key permissions:

chmod 400 key.pem


• Connect using SSH:

ssh -i key.pem ubuntu@<public-ip>


(Use ec2-user instead of ubuntu for Amazon Linux 2)

➤ Step 8: Run Shell Commands on the Server
➤ Check System Uptime
uptime


• Displays how long the server has been running.

➤ Install Apache Web Server
sudo apt update
sudo apt install apache2 -y


(For Amazon Linux 2 replace with:

sudo yum install httpd -y


)

➤ Start Apache Service
sudo systemctl start apache2
sudo systemctl enable apache2

➤ Step 9: Verify Apache

• Open a web browser and enter:

http://<public-ip>


• The Apache default page should load.
